06157nam a22009135i 9783110216042DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20092009gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979759457  a97831102160427 a10.1515/97831102160422doi  a(DE-B1597)36177  a(OCoLC)763156868  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh  aES 2502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27822:1 aGries, Stefan Th., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStatistics for Linguistics with R :bA Practical Introduction /cStefan Th. Gries. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (335 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v2080 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is an introduction to statistics for linguists using the open source software R. It is aimed at students and instructors/professors with little or no statistical background and is written in a non-technical and reader-friendly/accessible style. It first introduces in detail the overall logic underlying quantitative studies: exploration, hypothesis formulation and operationalization, and the notion and meaning of significance tests. It then introduces some basics of the software R relevant to statistical data analysis. A chapter on descriptive statistics explains how summary statistics for frequencies, averages, and correlations are generated with R and how they are graphically represented best. A chapter on analytical statistics explains how statistical tests are performed in R on the basis of many different linguistic case studies: For nearly every single example, it is explained what the structure of the test looks like, how hypotheses are formulated, explored, and tested for statistical significance, how the results are graphically represented, and how one would summarize them in a paper/article. A chapter on selected multifactorial methods introduces how more complex research designs can be studied: methods for the study of multifactorial frequency data, correlations, tests for means, and binary response data are discussed and exemplified step-by-step. Also, the exploratory approach of hierarchical cluster analysis is illustrated in detail. The book comes with many exercises, boxes with short think breaks and warnings, recommendations for further study, and answer keys as well as a statistics for linguists newsgroup on the companion website. The volume is aimed at beginners on every level of linguistic education: undergraduate students, graduate students, and instructors/professors and can be used in any research methods and statistics class for linguists. It presupposes no quantitative/statistical knowledge whatsoever and, unlike most competing books, begins at step 1 for every method and explains everything explicitly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aLinguisticsxStatistical methods. 0aR (Computer program language). 4aKorpuslinguistik. 4aLinguistische Datenverarbeitung. 4aStatistische Analyse. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCorpus Linguistics.  aLinguistic Data.  aStatistic Analysis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Linguistics and Semiotics  2000-2014 (EN)z978311023845708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 2000 - 2014z9783110636970oZDB-23-DLS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Backlist 2000-2015z978311074296108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PA